{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Buddhism expert: no disambiguation TN needed for category theory",
    "content": "**No TN needed. The context disambiguates immediately.**\n\nThe moment the reader sees \"objects,\" \"morphisms,\" \"functors,\" and mathematical notation, they know this is mathematical category theory, not Kantian categories. Any philosophically literate reader already knows these are different things that share a name. A disambiguation note would be patronizing -- like warning the reader that \"set theory\" is not about tennis sets.\n\nFurthermore, the author says the philosophical overlap is *intentional*. A TN saying \"not to be confused with Kant's categories\" would actively discourage the reader from noticing a resonance the author wants them to notice.\n\nIf anything is needed, it belongs in a general introduction to the collection, not a TN at the point of first use.\n"
  }
}
